Comment: simmbts said "2015. A couple of days ago were my three years anniversary of living in New York City with Hazel the dachshund.  I could list a couple of things that I accomplished while living in such a tough city but I'm going to list just one accomplishment that I think that matter to me the most.  While living in this city, I was lost and confused with my identity and what I was destined to do.  After awhile, I did nothing but beat myself up for not feeling enough and always wondered when I'd feel satisfied with life but I learned that I'll never be satisfied unless I start with myself.  I met my boyfriend through a mutual friend and he was the first person to ever tell me that it's okay to be me, the person I was always afraid to be.  I was introduced to yoga and it was an extra push to feel that it's okay to me so I started practicing compassion, kindness, and love toward to myself so I could feel like I have a purpose to be alive on this planet. I learned to let go of my past and to worry less about what my future is going to be.  My biggest accomplishment is that I finally broke down that gigantic wall of concrete around of my heart and allow it to expand and be shared with everybody else.  Life is too short to feel contained and to be afraid to pursue whatever it is that we want. If we could just accept ourselves for who we are and take risks this year to change for the better then we'll see the world for what it is.  It's a world filled with miracles and we are a huge part of it.  We are alive and breathing so start with a step out of your comfort zone and face those fears and emotions that you always run away from. Pursue everything that you dreamt of but first you would have to let go everything that's holding you back; your past and your expectations of the future.  Be present and embrace yourself. Everything takes practice so start practicing compassion, kindness, and love toward yourself then everything else will seem a lot easier to deal with.  This year I will  become a yoga teacher and share my gifts with you and everybody else. I was born for this."

Comment: brooklyntank718 said "Move them hips!! üòú Functions of the Hip Flexor

The hip flexor's main function is to help the hip joints move properly in their full range. The hip flexor helps you draw your leg to your torso, and also helps you move your legs from side to side and backwards. The hip flexor is the muscle group that connects your legs to your torso and lower body, and allows your legs to move in conjunction with your torso. The hip flexor also serves to stabilize your hips and lower body, keeping the joints of your pelvis and lumbar spine strong.

Consequences of Poor Hip Flexor Health

If your hip flexors are overdeveloped, tight, stiff or short, you'll suffer from lower back pain and hip pain. You could experience a limited range of motion in the hips and lower back. That's because tight hip flexors pull your pelvis into an unnatural forward tilt, which in turn pulls your lumbar spine out of alignment, causing lower back pain.

The hip flexor is a major stabilizer of the lower body, so if your hip flexor is too weak you'll suffer from poor balance and postural problems. You may have problems with your hip joints and frequent misalignments in your lumbar spine. You'll have trouble standing and walking for long periods of time, and you may have problems with your gait. üîµKeeping Your Hip Flexors Healthy

It's important to keep your hip flexors strong as well as flexible. Yoga, sit ups and leg lifts will help strengthen your hip flexors/core If you can perform leg lifts while dangling from a pull up bar, then this is an excellent way to strengthen your hip flexors. Just remember to keep your spine straight to prevent back injury; if you feel your spine bending as you lift your legs, then you've lifted far enough. ‚ö™Ô∏èYou should also stretch your hip flexors regularly to keep them long, loose and supple. Low lunges (in which you place your rear knee on the floor), butterfly stretches and the Pigeon Pose from yoga are all good ways to stretch your hip flexors. #brooklyntank718 #shredz"
